le="View this template">v</abbr></a></li>\n<li class="nv-talk"><a href="/w/index.php?title=Template_talk:Vajrayana&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Template talk:Vajrayana (page does not exist)"><abbr title="Discuss this template">t</abbr></a></li>\n<li class="nv-edit"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Vajrayana&amp;action=edit"><abbr title="Edit this template">e</abbr></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n<p>The <b>Kalachakra</b> (<a href="/wiki/Sanskrit" title="Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a> \xe0\xa4\x95\xe0\xa4\xbe\xe0\xa4\xb2\xe0\xa4\x9a\xe0\xa4\x95\xe0\xa5\x8d\xe0\xa4\xb0 <span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">K\xc4\x81lacakra</span>, <a href="/wiki/Tibetan_alphabet" title="Tibetan alphabet">Tibetan</a>: <span lang="bo" style="font-family: \'Qomolangma-Dunhuang\', \'Qomolangma-Uchen Sarchen\', \'Qomolangma-Uchen Sarchung\', \'Qomolangma-Uchen Suring\', \'Qomolangma-Uchen Sutung\', \'Qomolangma-Title\', \'Qomolangma-Subtitle\', \'Qomolangma-Woodblock\', \'DDC Uchen\', \'DDC Rinzin\', Kailash, Jomolhari, \'TCRC Youtso Unicode\', \'Tibetan Machine Uni\', Wangdi29, \'Noto Sans Tibetan\', \'Microsoft Himalaya\'; font-size:1.25em; vertical-align:top; word-wrap: break-word;" xml:lang="bo">\xe0\xbd\x91\xe0\xbd\xb4\xe0\xbd\xa6\xe0\xbc\x8b\xe0\xbd\x80\xe0\xbe\xb1\xe0\xbd\xb2\xe0\xbc\x8b\xe0\xbd\xa0\xe0\xbd\x81\xe0\xbd\xbc\xe0\xbd\xa2\xe0\xbc\x8b\xe0\xbd\xa3\xe0\xbd\xbc\xe0\xbc\x8d</span>,&#160;<a href="/wiki/Wylie_transliteration" title="Wylie transliteration">Wylie</a>: <i>dus kyi \'khor lo</i>; <a href="/wiki/Mongolian_language" title="Mongolian language">Mongolian</a>: <span lang="mn" xml:lang="mn">\xd0\xa6\xd0\xbe\xd0\xb3\xd1\x82 \xd0\xa6\xd0\xb0\xd0\xb3\xd0\xb8\xd0\xb9\xd0\xbd \xd0\xa5\xd2\xaf\xd1\x80\xd0\xb4\xd1\x8d\xd0\xbd</span> <i>Tsogt Tsagiin Hurden</i>; <a href="/wiki/Chinese_language" title="Chinese language">Chinese</a>: <span lang="zh" xml:lang="zh">\xe6\x99\x82\xe8\xbc\xaa</span>) is a term used in <a href="/wiki/Vajrayana" title="Vajrayana">Vajrayana Buddhism</a> that means <a href="/wiki/Wheel_of_time" title="Wheel of time">wheel of time</a> or "time-cycles".</p>\n<p>"K\xc4\x81lacakra" is usually used to refer to a very complex teaching and practice in <a href="/wiki/Tibetan_Buddhism" title="Tibetan Buddhism">Tibetan Buddhism</a>. Although the teaching is very advanced and <a href="/wiki/Esotericism" class="mw-redirect" title="Esotericism">esoteric</a>, there is a tradition of offering it to large public audiences.</p>\n<p></p>\n<div id="toc" class="toc">\n<div class="toctitle">\n<h2>Contents</h2>\n</div>\n<ul>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-1"><a href="#K.C4.81lacakra_tradition"><span class="tocnumber">1</span> <span class="toctext">K\xc4\x81lacakra tradition</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-2"><a href="#Text_of_the_K.C4.81lacakra_Tantra"><span class="tocnumber">2</span> <span class="toctext">Text of the K\xc4\x81lacakra Tantra</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-3"><a href="#Ground_K.C4.81lacakra"><span class="tocnumber">2.1</span> <span class="toctext">Ground K\xc4\x81lacakra</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-4"><a href="#Path_and_fruition"><span class="tocnumber">2.2</span> <span class="toctext">Path and fruition</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-5"><a href="#Astrology"><span class="tocnumber">2.3</span> <span class="toctext">Astrology</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-6"><a href="#History_and_origin"><span class="tocnumber">3</span> <span class="toctext">History and origin</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-7"><a href="#Original_Teaching_in_India_and_Later_Teachings_in_Kingdom_of_Shambhala"><span class="tocnumber">3.1</span> <span class="toctext">Original Teaching in India and Later Teachings in Kingdom of Shambhala</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-8"><a href="#Chilupa.2FK.C4.81lacakrapada"><span class="tocnumber">3.2</span> <span class="toctext">Chilupa/K\xc4\x81lacakrapada</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-9"><a href="#Spread_to_Tibet"><span class="tocnumber">3.3</span> <span class="toctext">Spread to Tibet</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-10"><a href="#Practice"><span class="tocnumber">4</span> <span class="toctext">Practice</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-11"><a href="#Initiation"><span class="tocnumber">4.1</span> <span class="toctext">Initiation</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-12"><a href="#K.C4.81lacakra_practice_today_in_the_Tibetan_Buddhist_schools"><span class="tocnumber">4.2</span> <span class="toctext">K\xc4\x81lacakra practice today in the Tibetan Buddhist schools</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class="toclevel-3 tocsection-13"><a href="#Gelugpa"><span class="tocnumber">4.2.1</span> <span class="toctext">Gelugpa</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-14"><a href="#Kagyu"><span class="tocnumber">4.3</span> <span class="toctext">Kagyu</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-15"><a href="#Nyingma"><span class="tocnumber">4.4</span> <span class="toctext">Nyingma</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-16"><a href="#Sakya"><span class="tocnumber">4.5</span> <span class="toctext">Sakya</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-17"><a href="#Jonang"><span class="tocnumber">4.6</span> <span class="toctext">Jonang</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-18"><a href="#Controversy"><span class="tocnumber">5</span> <span class="toctext">Controversy</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-19"><a href="#Prophesies_on_Holy_War"><span class="tocnumber">5.1</span> <span class="toctext">Prophesies on Holy War</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-20"><a href="#Symbolical_meaning"><span class="tocnumber">5.2</span> <span class="toctext">Symbolical meaning</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-21"><a href="#Iconography"><span class="tocnumber">5.3</span> <span class="toctext">Iconography</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-22"><a href="#See_also"><span class="tocnumber">6</span> <span class="toctext">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-23"><a href="#References"><span class="tocnumber">7</span> <span class="toctext">References</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-24"><a href="#Sources"><span class="tocnumber">8</span> <span class="toctext">Sources</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-25"><a href="#External_links"><span class="tocnumber">9</span> <span class="toctext">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<p></p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="K.C4.81lacakra_tradition">K\xc4\x81lacakra tradition</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: K\xc4\x81lacakra tradition">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>K\xc4\x81lacakra refers both to a patron Tantric deity or <a href="/wiki/I%E1%B9%A3%E1%B9%ADadevat%C4%81_(Buddhism)" class="mw-redirect" title="I\xe1\xb9\xa3\xe1\xb9\xadadevat\xc4\x81 (Buddhism)">i\xe1\xb9\xa3\xe1\xb9\xadadevat\xc4\x81</a>, (<a href="/wiki/Wylie_transliteration" title="Wylie transliteration">Wylie</a>: <i>yi dam</i>) of Vajrayana Buddhism and to the philosophies and meditation practices contained within the <i>K\xc4\x81lacakra Tantra</i> and its many commentaries. The <i>K\xc4\x81lacakra Tantra</i> is more properly called the <i>K\xc4\x81lacakra Laghutantra</i>, and is said to be an abridged form of an original text, the <i>K\xc4\x81lacakra M\xc5\xablatantra</i> which is no longer extant. Some Buddhist masters assert that K\xc4\x81lacakra is the most advanced form of Vajrayana practice; it certainly is one of the most complex systems within tantric Buddhism.</p>\n<p>The K\xc4\x81lacakra tradition revolves around the concept of time (<a href="/wiki/K%C4%81la_(time)" title="K\xc4\x81la (time)">k\xc4\x81la</a>) and cycles (<a href="/wiki/Chakra" title="Chakra">chakra</a>): from the cycles of the planets,<sup id="cite_ref-Rite_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Rite-1">[1]</a></sup> to the cycles of human breathing, it teaches the practice of working with the most subtle energies within one\'s body on the path to enlightenment.</p>\n<p>The K\xc4\x81lacakra deity represents a <a href="/wiki/Buddhahood" title="Buddhahood">buddhahood</a> and thus <a href="/wiki/Omniscience" title="Omniscience">omniscience</a>. Since K\xc4\x81lacakra <i>is</i> time and everything is under the influence of time, K\xc4\x81lacakra knows all. K\xc4\x81lacakri, his spiritual consort and complement, is aware of everything that is timeless, not time-bound or out of the realm of time. In <a href="/wiki/Yab-Yum" title="Yab-Yum">Yab-Yum</a>, they are temporality and atemporality conjoined. Similarly, the wheel is without beginning or end. The term "wheel" evoked herewith is a principal polyvalent sign, teaching tool, organising metaphor and iconographic device within <a href="/wiki/Indian_religions" title="Indian religions">Indian religions</a>. Some "wheel" cognates are the <a href="/wiki/Ashtamangala" title="Ashtamangala">a\xe1\xb9\xa3\xe1\xb9\xadama\xe1\xb9\x85gala</a> symbol of the <a href="/wiki/Dharmacakra" class="mw-redirect" title="Dharmacakra">dharmacakra</a>, <a href="/wiki/Vishnu" title="Vishnu">Vishnu</a>\'s <a href="/wiki/Sudarshana_Chakra" title="Sudarshana Chakra">Sudarshana Chakra</a> and the theory of <a href="/wiki/Sa%E1%B9%83s%C4%81ra" title="Sa\xe1\xb9\x83s\xc4\x81ra">sa\xe1\xb9\x83s\xc4\x81ra</a>.</p>\n<p>K\xc4\x81lacakra refers to many different traditions: for example, it is related to Hindu <a href="/wiki/Shaivism" title="Shaivism">Shaiva</a>, <a href="/wiki/Samkhya" title="Samkhya">Samkhya</a>, <a href="/wiki/Vaishnavism" title="Vaishnavism">Vaishnava</a>, <a href="/wiki/Vedas" title="Vedas">Vedic</a>, <a href="/wiki/Upanishads" title="Upanishads">Upanishadic</a> and <a href="/wiki/Puranas" title="Puranas">Puranic</a> traditions and also to Jainism. The K\xc4\x81lacakra mandala includes deities which are equally accepted by <a href="/wiki/Hindu" title="Hindu">Hindus</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jainism" title="Jainism">Jains</a> and Buddhists.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup></p>\n<p>The K\xc4\x81lacakra deity resides in the center of the mandala in his palace consisting of four mandalas, one within the other: the mandalas of body, speech, and mind, and in the very center, wisdom and great bliss.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup> The K\xc4\x81lacakra sand mandala is dedicated to both individual and world peace and physical balance. The Dalai Lama explains: \xe2\x80\x9cIt is a way of planting a seed, and the seed will have karmic effect. One doesn\xe2\x80\x99t need to be present at the Kalachakra ceremony in order to receive its benefits.\xe2\x80\x9d<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (July 2014)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Text_of_the_K.C4.81lacakra_Tantra">Text of the K\xc4\x81lacakra Tantra</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Text of the K\xc4\x81lacakra Tantra">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class="thumb tright">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Kalachakradeitydis.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/0/0e/Kalachakradeitydis.jpg/220px-Kalachakradeitydis.jpg" width="220" height="293" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/0/0e/Kalachakradeitydis.jpg 1.5x" data-file-width="250" data-file-height="333" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Kalachakradeitydis.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>\nK\xc4\x81lacakra Deity with consort <a href="/w/index.php?title=Visvamata&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Visvamata (page does not exist)">Visvamata</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>The K\xc4\x81lacakra Tantra is divided into five chapters.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">[4]</a></sup></p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Ground_K.C4.81lacakra">Ground K\xc4\x81lacakra</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Ground K\xc4\x81lacakra">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>The first two chapters are considered the "ground K\xc4\x81lacakra." The first chapter deals with what is called the "outer K\xc4\x81lacakra"\xe2\x80\x94the physical world\xe2\x80\x93 and in particular the calculation system for the K\xc4\x81lacakra calendar, the birth and death of universes, our solar system and the workings of the elements.</p>\n<p>The second chapter deals with the "inner K\xc4\x81lacakra," and concerns processes of human gestation and birth, the classification of the functions within the human body and experience, and the vajra-kaya; the expression of human physical existence in terms of channels, winds, drops and so forth. Human experience is by some described in terms of four mind states: waking, dream, deep sleep, and a fourth state which is available through the energies of sexual orgasm. The potentials (drops) which give rise to these states are described, together with the processes that flow from them.</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Path_and_fruition">Path and fruition</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Path and fruition">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>The last three chapters describe the "other" or "alternative K\xc4\x81lacakra," and deal with the path and fruition. The third chapter deals with the preparation for the meditation practices of the system: the initiations of K\xc4\x81lacakra. The fourth chapter explains the actual meditation practices themselves, both the meditation on the mandala and its deities in the generation stage practices, and the perfection or completion stage practices of the <a href="/wiki/Six_Yogas" class="mw-redirect" title="Six Yogas">Six Yogas</a>. The fifth and final chapter describes the state of enlightenment (Relijin) that results from the practice.</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Astrology">Astrology</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Astrology">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>The phrase "as it is outside, so it is within the body" is often found in the K\xc4\x81lacakra tantra to emphasize the similarities and correspondence between human beings and the <a href="/wiki/Cosmos" title="Cosmos">cosmos</a>; this concept is the basis for K\xc4\x81lacakra <a href="/wiki/Astrology" title="Astrology">astrology</a>, but also for more profound connections and interdependence as taught in the K\xc4\x81lacakra literature.</p>\n<p>In Tibet, the K\xc4\x81lacakra astrological system is one of the main building blocks in the composition of <a href="/wiki/Tibetan_calendar" title="Tibetan calendar">Tibetan astrological calendars</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup> The astrology in the K\xc4\x81lacakra is not like the Western system, in that it employs complicated astronomical calculations to determine, for example, the exact location of the planets.</p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History_and_origin">History and origin</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: History and origin">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class="thumb tright">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Rigdan_Tagpa.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Rigdan_Tagpa.jpg/220px-Rigdan_Tagpa.jpg" width="220" height="260" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Rigdan_Tagpa.jpg/330px-Rigdan_Tagpa.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Rigdan_Tagpa.jpg/440px-Rigdan_Tagpa.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1232" data-file-height="1456" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Rigdan_Tagpa.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>\nMa\xc3\xb1jushr\xc4\xabk\xc4\xabrti (<a href="/wiki/Tibetan_alphabet" title="Tibetan alphabet">Tibetan</a>: <span lang="bo" style="font-family: \'Qomolangma-Dunhuang\', \'Qomolangma-Uchen Sarchen\', \'Qomolangma-Uchen Sarchung\', \'Qomolangma-Uchen Suring\', \'Qomolangma-Uchen Sutung\', \'Qomolangma-Title\', \'Qomolangma-Subtitle\', \'Qomolangma-Woodblock\', \'DDC Uchen\', \'DDC Rinzin\', Kailash, Jomolhari, \'TCRC Youtso Unicode\', \'Tibetan Machine Uni\', Wangdi29, \'Noto Sans Tibetan\', \'Microsoft Himalaya\'; font-size:1.25em; vertical-align:top; word-wrap: break-word;" xml:lang="bo">\xe0\xbd\xa0\xe0\xbd\x87\xe0\xbd\x98\xe0\xbc\x8b\xe0\xbd\x91\xe0\xbd\x94\xe0\xbd\xa3\xe0\xbc\x8b\xe0\xbd\x82\xe0\xbe\xb2\xe0\xbd\x82\xe0\xbd\xa6\xe0\xbc\x8b\xe0\xbd\x94</span>, <a href="/wiki/THL_Simplified_Phonetic_Transcription" title="THL Simplified Phonetic Transcription">THL</a> <i>Jampel Drakpa</i>), <a href="/wiki/Kings_of_Shambhala" title="Kings of Shambhala">King of Shambhala</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Original_Teaching_in_India_and_Later_Teachings_in_Kingdom_of_Shambhala">Original Teaching in India and Later Teachings in Kingdom of Shambhala</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Original Teaching in India and Later Teachings in Kingdom of Shambhala">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>According to the <i>K\xc4\x81lacakra tantra</i>, <a href="/wiki/Suchandra" title="Suchandra">Suchandra</a>, <a href="/wiki/Dharmaraja_(Buddhism)" title="Dharmaraja (Buddhism)">dharmaraja</a> of <a href="/wiki/Shambhala" title="Shambhala">Shambhala</a>, requested that <a href="/wiki/Gautama_Buddha" title="Gautama Buddha">Gautama Buddha</a> teach him how to practice the <a href="/wiki/Dharma" title="Dharma">dharma</a> without renouncing worldly responsibilities.</p>\n<p>In response to his request, the Buddha taught the first K\xc4\x81lacakra root tantra in <a href="/wiki/Dharanikota" title="Dharanikota">Dharanikota</a> (near modern <a href="/wiki/Amaravathi_village,_Guntur_district" class="mw-redirect" title="Amaravathi village, Guntur district">Amaravathi</a>) in 5th century B.C. of southeastern <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">India</a>, supposedly bilocating (appearing in two places at once) at the same time as he was also delivering the <a href="/wiki/Prajnaparamita" title="Prajnaparamita">Praj\xc3\xb1\xc4\x81p\xc4\x81ramit\xc4\x81</a> sutras at <a href="/wiki/Griddhraj_Parvat" class="mw-redirect" title="Griddhraj Parvat">Griddhraj Parvat</a> in <a href="/wiki/Bihar" title="Bihar">Bihar</a>. Along with King Suchandra, ninety-six minor kings and emissaries from Shambhala were also said to have received the teachings. The <i>K\xc4\x81lacakra</i> thus passed directly to <a href="/wiki/Shambhala" title="Shambhala">Shambhala</a>, where it was held exclusively for hundreds of years. Later <a href="/wiki/Kings_of_Shambhala" title="Kings of Shambhala">Kings of Shambhala</a>, Ma\xc3\xb1jushr\xc4\xabk\xc4\xabrti and Pundarika, are said to have condensed and simplified the teachings into the <i>\xc5\x9ari K\xc4\x81lacakra</i> or <i>Laghutantra</i> and its main commentary, the <i><a href="/wiki/Vimalaprabha" title="Vimalaprabha">Vimalaprabha</a></i>, which remain extant today as the heart of the K\xc4\x81lacakra literature. Fragments of the original tantra have survived; the most significant fragment, the <i>Sekkodesha</i>, was commented upon by <a href="/wiki/Naropa" title="Naropa">Naropa</a>.</p>\n<p>Ma\xc3\xb1jushr\xc4\xabk\xc4\xabrti (<a href="/wiki/Tibetan_alphabet" title="Tibetan alphabet">Tibetan</a>: <span lang="bo" style="font-family: \'Qomolangma-Dunhuang\', \'Qomolangma-Uchen Sarchen\', \'Qomolangma-Uchen Sarchung\', \'Qomolangma-Uchen Suring\', \'Qomolangma-Uchen Sutung\', \'Qomolangma-Title\', \'Qomolangma-Subtitle\', \'Qomolangma-Woodblock\', \'DDC Uchen\', \'DDC Rinzin\', Kailash, Jomolhari, \'TCRC Youtso Unicode\', \'Tibetan Machine Uni\', Wangdi29, \'Noto Sans Tibetan\', \'Microsoft Himalaya\'; font-size:1.25em; vertical-align:top; word-wrap: break-word;" xml:lang="bo">\xe0\xbd\xa0\xe0\xbd\x87\xe0\xbd\x98\xe0\xbc\x8b\xe0\xbd\x91\xe0\xbd\x94\xe0\xbd\xa3\xe0\xbc\x8b\xe0\xbd\x82\xe0\xbe\xb2\xe0\xbd\x82\xe0\xbd\xa6\xe0\xbc\x8b\xe0\xbd\x94</span>, <a href="/wiki/THL_Simplified_Phonetic_Transcription" title="THL Simplified Phonetic Transcription">THL</a> <i>Jampel Drakpa</i>) is said to have been born in 159 BCE and ruled over Shambhala, which had 300,510 followers of the <a href="/wiki/Mleccha" title="Mleccha">Mleccha</a> religion living in it, some of whom worshiped the sun. He is said to have expelled all the heretics from his dominions but later, after hearing their petitions, allowed them to return. For their benefit, and the benefit of all living beings, he explained the <i>K\xc4\x81lacakra</i> teachings. In 59 BCE he abdicated his throne to his son, Pu\xe1\xb9\x87\xe1\xb8\x8d\xc4\x81rika, and died soon afterwards, entering the <a href="/wiki/Sambhogak%C4%81ya" title="Sambhogak\xc4\x81ya">sambhogak\xc4\x81ya</a> of <a href="/wiki/Buddhahood" title="Buddhahood">Buddhahood</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup></p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Chilupa.2FK.C4.81lacakrapada">Chilupa/K\xc4\x81lacakrapada</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Chilupa/K\xc4\x81lacakrapada">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>There are currently two main traditions of <i>K\xc4\x81lacakra</i>, the Ra lineage (<a href="/wiki/Wylie_transliteration" title="Wylie transliteration">Wylie</a>: <i>rva lugs</i>) and the Dro lineage (<a href="/wiki/Wylie_transliteration" title="Wylie transliteration">Wylie</a>: <i>bro lugs</i>). Although there were many translations of the <i>K\xc4\x81lacakra</i> texts from Sanskrit into Tibetan, the Ra and Dro translations are considered to be the most reliable (more about the two lineages below). The two lineages offer slightly differing accounts of how the <i>K\xc4\x81lacakra</i> teachings returned to India from Shambhala.</p>\n<p>In both traditions, the <i>K\xc4\x81lacakra</i> and its related commentaries (sometimes referred to as the <i>Bodhisattvas Corpus</i>) were returned to India in 966<small>CE</small> by an Indian <a href="/wiki/Pandit" title="Pandit">pandit</a>. In the Ra tradition this figure is known as Chilupa, and in the Dro tradition as K\xc4\x81lacakrapada the Greater. Scholars such as Helmut Hoffman have suggested they are the same person. The first masters of the tradition disguised themselves with pseudonyms, so the Indian oral traditions recorded by the Tibetans contain a mass of contradictions.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (July 2012)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></p>\n<p>Chilupa/K\xc4\x81lacakrapada is said to have set out to receive the K\xc4\x81lacakra teachings in Shambhala, along the journey to which he encountered the Kulika (Shambhala) king Durjaya manifesting as <a href="/wiki/Manjusri" class="mw-redirect" title="Manjusri">Manjusri</a>, who conferred the K\xc4\x81lacakra initiation on him, based on his pure motivation.</p>\n<p>Upon returning to India, Chilupa/K\xc4\x81lacakrapada is said to have defeated in debate Nadapada (Tib. <a href="/wiki/Naropa" title="Naropa">Naropa</a>), abbot of <a href="/wiki/Nalanda" title="Nalanda">Nalanda</a>, a great center of Buddhist thought at that time. Chilupa/K\xc4\x81lacakrapada then initiated Nadapada (who became known as K\xc4\x81lacakrapada the Lesser) into the <i>K\xc4\x81lacakra</i>, and the tradition thereafter in India and Tibet stems from these two. Nadapada established the teachings as legitimate in the eyes of the Nalanda community, and initiated into the <i>K\xc4\x81lacakra</i> such masters as <a href="/wiki/Ati%C5%9Ba" title="Ati\xc5\x9ba">Ati\xc5\x9ba</a> (who, in turn, initiated the K\xc4\x81lacakra master <a href="/w/index.php?title=Pindo_Acharya&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Pindo Acharya (page does not exist)">Pindo Acharya</a> (Tib. <i>Pitopa</i>)).</p>\n<p>A Tibetan history, the <i>Dpag bsam ljon bzang</i>, as well as architectural evidence, indicates that the <a href="/wiki/Ratnagiri,_Odisha" title="Ratnagiri, Odisha">Ratnagiri, Odisha</a> <a href="/wiki/Mahavihara" title="Mahavihara">mahavihara</a> was an important center for the dissemination of the <i>K\xc4\x81lacakratantra</i> in India.</p>\n<p>The <i>K\xc4\x81lacakra</i> tradition, along with all Buddhism, vanished from India in the wake of the <a href="/wiki/Muslim" title="Muslim">Muslim</a> invasions, surviving only in <a href="/wiki/Nepal" title="Nepal">Nepal</a>.</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Spread_to_Tibet">Spread to Tibet</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Spread to Tibet">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<div class="thumb tright">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Kala_Chakra.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e3/Kala_Chakra.jpg/220px-Kala_Chakra.jpg" width="220" height="325" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e3/Kala_Chakra.jpg/330px-Kala_Chakra.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e3/Kala_Chakra.jpg/440px-Kala_Chakra.jpg 2x" data-file-width="541" data-file-height="800" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Kala_Chakra.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>\nK\xc4\x81lacakra statue in <a href="/wiki/American_Museum_of_Natural_History" title="American Museum of Natural History">American Museum of Natural History</a>, <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>The Dro lineage was established in Tibet by a <a href="/wiki/Kashmir" title="Kashmir">Kashmiri</a> disciple of Nalandapa named Pandita Somanatha, who traveled to Tibet in 1027 (or 1064<small>CE</small>, depending on the calendar used), and his translator <b>Dro</b> <a href="/wiki/Lotsawa" title="Lotsawa">Lotsawa</a> Sh\xc3\xa9rap Drak <a href="/wiki/Wylie_transliteration" title="Wylie transliteration">Wylie</a>: <i>\'bro lo tsa ba shes rab grags</i>, from which it takes its name. The Ra lineage was brought to Tibet by another Kashmiri disciple of Nadapada named Samantashri, and translated by <b>Ra</b> Lotsawa Ch\xc3\xb6rap <a href="/wiki/Wylie_transliteration" title="Wylie transliteration">Wylie</a>: <i>rwa lo tsa ba chos rab</i>.</p>\n<p>The Ra lineage became particularly important in the <a href="/wiki/Sakya" title="Sakya">Sakya</a> school of Tibetan Buddhism, where it was held by such prominent masters as <a href="/wiki/Sakya_Pandita" title="Sakya Pandita">Sakya Pandita</a> (1182\xe2\x80\x931251), <a href="/wiki/Drog%C3%B6n_Ch%C3%B6gyal_Phagpa" title="Drog\xc3\xb6n Ch\xc3\xb6gyal Phagpa">Drog\xc3\xb6n Ch\xc3\xb6gyal Phagpa</a> (1235\xe2\x80\x931280), <a href="/wiki/Buton_Rinchen_Drub" title="Buton Rinchen Drub">But\xc3\xb6n Rinchen Drup</a> (1290\xe2\x80\x931364), and <a href="/wiki/Dolpopa_Sherab_Gyaltsen" title="Dolpopa Sherab Gyaltsen">D\xc3\xb6lpopa Sh\xc3\xa9rap Gyeltsen</a> (1292\xe2\x80\x931361). The latter two, both of whom also held the Dro lineage, are particularly well known expositors of the <i>K\xc4\x81lacakra</i> in Tibet, the practice of which is said to have greatly informed D\xc3\xb6lpopa\'s exposition of <a href="/wiki/Shentong" class="mw-redirect" title="Shentong">shentong</a>. A strong emphasis on <i>K\xc4\x81lacakra</i> practice and exposition of the zhentong view were the principal distinguishing characteristics of the <a href="/wiki/Jonang" title="Jonang">Jonang</a> school that traces its roots to D\xc3\xb6lpopa Sh\xc3\xa9rap Gyeltsen.</p>\n<p>The teaching of the <i>K\xc4\x81lacakra</i> was further advanced by the great Jonang scholar <a href="/wiki/Taranatha" title="Taranatha">Taranatha</a> (1575\xe2\x80\x931634). In the 17th century, the government of the <a href="/wiki/5th_Dalai_Lama" title="5th Dalai Lama">5th Dalai Lama</a> outlawed the Jonang school, closing down or forcibly converting most of its monasteries. The writings of Dolpopa Sherab Gyaltsen, Taranatha, and other prominent zhentong scholars were banned. Ironically, it was also at this time that the Gelug school absorbed much of the Jonang <i>K\xc4\x81lacakra</i> tradition.</p>\n<p>Today, K\xc4\x81lacakra is practiced by all schools of Tibetan Buddhism, although it appears most prominently in the Gelug lineage. It is the main tantric practice for the Jonangpa, whose school persists to this day with a small number of monasteries in <a href="/wiki/Kham" title="Kham">Kham</a>, <a href="/wiki/Qinghai" title="Qinghai">Qinghai</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sichuan" title="Sichuan">Sichuan</a>. Efforts are under way to have the Jonang tradition be recognized officially as a fifth tradition of Tibetan Buddhism.</p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Practice">Practice</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Practice">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class="thumb tright">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Kalachakra_Dance_Mask.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d5/Kalachakra_Dance_Mask.JPG/220px-Kalachakra_Dance_Mask.JPG" width="220" height="244" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d5/Kalachakra_Dance_Mask.JPG/330px-Kalachakra_Dance_Mask.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d5/Kalachakra_Dance_Mask.JPG/440px-Kalachakra_Dance_Mask.JPG 2x" data-file-width="1824" data-file-height="2019" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Kalachakra_Dance_Mask.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>\nKalachakra Dance Mask</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Initiation">Initiation</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Initiation">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Ancient mask from the kalachakra dances, where ten monks dress as the ten world deities and perform a dance of consecrating the location of the mandala in preparation for the initiation ritual, after asking the earth goddess for permission to erect it at a particular site.</p>\n<div class="thumb tright">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Kalachakra0045_tiny.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Kalachakra0045_tiny.jpg/220px-Kalachakra0045_tiny.jpg" width="220" height="146" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Kalachakra0045_tiny.jpg/330px-Kalachakra0045_tiny.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Kalachakra0045_tiny.jpg/440px-Kalachakra0045_tiny.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1090" data-file-height="725" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Kalachakra0045_tiny.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>\nMonks attending the January 2003 K\xc4\x81lacakra initiation in <a href="/wiki/Bodh_Gaya" title="Bodh Gaya">Bodh Gaya</a>, India</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>As in all vajryana practices, the K\xc4\x81lacakra initiations empower the disciple to practice the K\xc4\x81lacakra tantra in the service of attaining Buddhahood. There are two main sets of initiations in K\xc4\x81lacakra, eleven in all. The first of these two sets concerns preparation for the generation stage meditations of K\xc4\x81lacakra. The second concerns preparation for the completion stage meditations known as the Six Yogas of K\xc4\x81lacakra. Attendees who don\'t intend to carry out the practice are often only given the lower seven initiations.</p>\n<p>The K\xc4\x81lacakra sand <a href="/wiki/Mandala" title="Mandala">Mandala</a> is dedicated to both individual and world peace and physical balance. The Dalai Lama explains: "It is a way of planting a seed, and the seed will have karmic effect. One doesn\'t need to be present at the K\xc4\x81lacakra ceremony in order to receive its benefits."<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup></p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="K.C4.81lacakra_practice_today_in_the_Tibetan_Buddhist_schools">K\xc4\x81lacakra practice today in the Tibetan Buddhist schools</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: K\xc4\x81lacakra practice today in the Tibetan Buddhist schools">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>But\xc3\xb6n Rinchen Drup had considerable influence on the later development of the Gelug and Sakya traditions of K\xc4\x81lacakra and D\xc3\xb6lpopa on the development of the Jonang tradition on which the Kagyu, Nyingma, and the Tsarpa branch of the Sakya draw. The Nyingma and Kagyu rely heavily on the extensive, Jonang-influenced K\xc4\x81lacakra commentaries of <a href="/wiki/Jamgon_Ju_Mipham_Gyatso" title="Jamgon Ju Mipham Gyatso">Jamgon Ju Mipham Gyatso</a> and Jamgon Kongtrul, both of whom took a strong interest in the tradition. The Tsarpa branch of the Sakya maintain the practice lineage for the six branch yoga of K\xc4\x81lacakra in the Jonang tradition.</p>\n<p>There were many other influences and much cross-fertilization between the different traditions, and indeed the Dalai Lama asserted that it is acceptable for those initiated in one K\xc4\x81lacakra tradition to practice in others.</p>\n<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Gelugpa">Gelugpa</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Gelugpa">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>\n<div class="thumb tright">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:DalaiLama0054_tiny.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/DalaiLama0054_tiny.jpg/220px-DalaiLama0054_tiny.jpg" width="220" height="150" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/DalaiLama0054_tiny.jpg/330px-DalaiLama0054_tiny.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/DalaiLama0054_tiny.jpg/440px-DalaiLama0054_tiny.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1104" data-file-height="754" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:DalaiLama0054_tiny.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>\nThe <a href="/wiki/Dalai_Lama" title="Dalai Lama">Dalai Lama</a> presiding over the K\xc4\x81lacakra initiation in Bodh Gaya, India, in January 2003.</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>The <a href="/wiki/Dalai_Lama" title="Dalai Lama">Dalai Lamas</a> have had specific interest in the K\xc4\x81lacakra practice, particularly the <a href="/wiki/1st_Dalai_Lama" title="1st Dalai Lama">First</a>, <a href="/wiki/2nd_Dalai_Lama" title="2nd Dalai Lama">Second</a>, <a href="/wiki/7th_Dalai_Lama" title="7th Dalai Lama">Seventh</a>, <a href="/wiki/8th_Dalai_Lama" title="8th Dalai Lama">Eighth</a>, and the current (<a href="/wiki/14th_Dalai_Lama" title="14th Dalai Lama">Fourteenth</a>) Dalai Lamas. The present Dalai Lama has given over thirty K\xc4\x81lacakra initiations all over the world, and is the most prominent K\xc4\x81lacakra lineage holder alive today. Billed as the "K\xc4\x81lacakra for World Peace," they draw tens of thousands of people. Generally, it is unusual for tantric initiations to be given to large public assemblages, but the K\xc4\x81lacakra has always been an exception.</p>\n<p>The Dalai Lama, <a href="/wiki/Kalu_Rinpoche" title="Kalu Rinpoche">Kalu Rinpoche</a>, and others have stated that the public exposition of this tantra is necessary in the current degenerate age. The initiation may be received simply as a blessing for the majority of those attending, however, many of the more qualified attendees do take the commitments and subsequently engage in the practice.</p>\n<p><b>K\xc4\x81lacakra Initiations given by XIV Dalai Lama</b> .<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">[8]</a></sup></p>\n<ul>\n<li>1. Norbu Lingka, Lhasa, Tibet, in May 1954</li>\n<li>2. Norbu Lingka, Lhasa, Tibet, in April 1956</li>\n<li>3. Dharamsala, India, in March 1970</li>\n<li>4. Bylakuppe, South India, in May 1971</li>\n<li>5. Bodh Gaya, India, in January 1974</li>\n<li>6. Leh, Ladakh, India, in September 1976</li>\n<li>7. Deer Park Buddhist Center, Madison, Wisconsin, USA, in July 1981</li>\n<li>8. Dirang, Arunachal Pradesh, India, in April 1983</li>\n<li>9. Lahaul &amp; Spiti, India, in August 1983</li>\n<li>10. Rikon, Switzerland, in July 1985</li>\n<li>11. Bodh Gaya, India, in December 1985</li>\n<li>12. Zanskar, Ladakh, India, in July 1988</li>\n<li>13. Los Angeles, USA, in July 1989</li>\n<li>14. Sarnath, India, in December 1990</li>\n<li>15. New York, USA, in October 1991</li>\n<li>16. <a href="/wiki/Kalpa,_Himachal_Pradesh" title="Kalpa, Himachal Pradesh">Kalpa, Himachal Pradesh</a>, India, in August 1992</li>\n<li>17. <a href="/wiki/Gangtok" title="Gangtok">Gangtok</a>, Sikkim, India, in April 1993</li>\n<li>18. <a href="/wiki/Jispa" title="Jispa">Jispa</a>, HP, India, in August 1994</li>\n<li>19. Barcelona, Spain, in December 1994</li>\n<li>20. Mundgod, South India, in January 1995</li>\n<li>21. Ulanbaator, Mongolia, in August 1995</li>\n<li>22. Tabo, HP, India, in June 1996</li>\n<li>23. Sydney, Australia, in September 1996</li>\n<li>24. Salugara, West Bengal, India, in December 1996.</li>\n<li>25. Bloomington, Indiana, USA, in August 1999.</li>\n<li>26. <a href="/wiki/Key_Monastery" title="Key Monastery">Key Monastery</a>, Spiti, Himachal Pradesh, India, in August 2000.<sup id="cite_ref-hplahaulspiti_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hplahaulspiti-9">[9]</a></sup></li>\n<li>27. Graz, Austria, in October 2002.</li>\n<li>28. Bodh Gaya, Bihar, India, in January 2003.</li>\n<li>29. Toronto, Canada, in April 2004.</li>\n<li>30. <a href="/wiki/Amaravathi_(village),_Guntur_district" title="Amaravathi (village), Guntur district">Amaravathi</a>, <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">India</a> in January 2006.</li>\n<li>31. Washington, DC, USA, in July 2011.</li>\n<li>32. <a href="/wiki/Bodh_Gaya" title="Bodh Gaya">Bodh Gaya</a>, India, in January 2012.</li>\n<li>33. <a href="/wiki/Leh" title="Leh">Leh</a> <a href="/wiki/Ladakh" title="Ladakh">Ladakh</a>, <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">India</a> July 2014</li>\n<li>34. Bodh Gaya, Bihar, India, in January 2017.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The 33rd Kalachakra ceremony was held in <a href="/wiki/Leh" title="Leh">Leh</a> town of <a href="/wiki/Jammu_and_Kashmir" title="Jammu and Kashmir">Jammu and Kashmir</a>, India from July 3 to July 12, 2014. About 150,000 devotees and 350,000 tourists were expected to participate in the festival.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup></p>\n<p><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kirti_Tsenshab_Rinpoche&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Kirti Tsenshab Rinpoche (page does not exist)">Kirti Tsenshab Rinpoche</a> (1926\xe2\x80\x932006), the <a href="/wiki/9th_Jebtsundamba_Khutughtu" title="9th Jebtsundamba Khutughtu">9th Jebtsundamba Khutughtu</a>, <a href="/w/index.php?title=Jhado_Rinpoche&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Jhado Rinpoche (page does not exist)">Jhado Rinpoche</a> and the late <a href="/w/index.php?title=Gen_Lamrimpa&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Gen Lamrimpa (page does not exist)">Gen Lamrimpa</a> (d. 2003) were also among prominent Gelugpa K\xc4\x81lacakra masters.</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Kagyu">Kagyu</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Kagyu">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<div class="thumb tright">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Kalou_Rimpoche_Montpellier_1987.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/aa/Kalou_Rimpoche_Montpellier_1987.jpg/220px-Kalou_Rimpoche_Montpellier_1987.jpg" width="220" height="283" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/aa/Kalou_Rimpoche_Montpellier_1987.jpg/330px-Kalou_Rimpoche_Montpellier_1987.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/aa/Kalou_Rimpoche_Montpellier_1987.jpg 2x" data-file-width="365" data-file-height="470" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Kalou_Rimpoche_Montpellier_1987.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>\n<b>Kalu Rinpoche</b> in 1987 at <i>Kagyu Rintchen Tcheu Ling</i> in <a href="/wiki/Montpellier" title="Montpellier">Montpellier</a>, <a href="/wiki/France" title="France">France</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>The K\xc4\x81lacakra tradition practiced in the Karma and <a href="/wiki/Shangpa_Kagyu" title="Shangpa Kagyu">Shangpa Kagyu</a> schools is derived from the Jonang tradition and was largely systematized by Jamg\xc3\xb6n Kongtr\xc3\xbcl, who wrote the text that is now used for empowerment. The 2nd and 3rd Jamgon Kongtrul (1954\xe2\x80\x931992) were also prominent K\xc4\x81lacakra lineage holders, with the 3rd Jamgon Kontrul giving the initiation publicly in North America on at least one occasion (Toronto 1990).<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">[11]</a></sup></p>\n<p>The chief K\xc4\x81lacakra lineage holder for the Kagyu lineage was <a href="/wiki/Kalu_Rinpoche" title="Kalu Rinpoche">Kalu Rinpoche</a> (1905\xe2\x80\x931990), who gave the initiation several times in Tibet, India, Europe and North America (e.g., New York 1982<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup>). Upon his death, this mantle was assumed by his heart son, <a href="/wiki/Bokar_Tulku_Rinpoche" title="Bokar Tulku Rinpoche">Bokar Tulku Rinpoche</a> (1940\xe2\x80\x932004), who in turn passed it on to Khenpo Lodro Donyo Rinpoche. Bokar Monastery, of which Donyo Rinpoche is now the head, features a K\xc4\x81lacakra stupa and is a prominent retreat center for K\xc4\x81lacakra practice in the Kagyu lineage.</p>\n<p><a href="/wiki/Tenga_Rinpoche" title="Tenga Rinpoche">Tenga Rinpoche</a> was also a prominent Kagyu holder of the K\xc4\x81lacakra; he gave the initiation in Grabnik, Poland in August, 2005.</p>\n<p><a href="/wiki/Lopon_Tsechu" title="Lopon Tsechu">Lopon Tsechu</a> performed K\xc4\x81lacakra initiations and build <a href="/w/index.php?title=K%C4%81lacakra_stupa&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="K\xc4\x81lacakra stupa (page does not exist)">K\xc4\x81lacakra stupa</a> in Karma Guen buddhist center in southern <a href="/wiki/Spain" title="Spain">Spain</a>. Another prominent K\xc4\x81lacakra master is the <a href="/wiki/Second_Beru_Khyentse" title="Second Beru Khyentse">Second Beru Khyentse</a>.</p>\n<p><a href="/wiki/Ch%C3%B6gyam_Trungpa" title="Ch\xc3\xb6gyam Trungpa">Ch\xc3\xb6gyam Trungpa</a>, while not a noted K\xc4\x81lacakra master, became increasingly involved later in his life with what he termed Shambhala teachings, derived in part from the K\xc4\x81lacakra tradition, in particular, the mind <a href="/wiki/Terma_(religion)" title="Terma (religion)">terma</a> which he received from the <a href="/wiki/Kalki" title="Kalki">Kalki</a>.</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Nyingma">Nyingma</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Nyingma">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Among the prominent recent and contemporary Nyingma K\xc4\x81lacakra masters are <a href="/wiki/Dzongsar_Khyentse_Ch%C3%B6kyi_Lodr%C3%B6" title="Dzongsar Khyentse Ch\xc3\xb6kyi Lodr\xc3\xb6">Dzongsar Khyentse Ch\xc3\xb6kyi Lodr\xc3\xb6</a> (1894\xe2\x80\x931959), <a href="/wiki/Dilgo_Khyentse" title="Dilgo Khyentse">Dilgo Khyentse</a> (1910\xe2\x80\x931991), and <a href="/wiki/Penor_Rinpoche" title="Penor Rinpoche">Penor Rinpoche</a> (1932\xe2\x80\x932009).</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Sakya">Sakya</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Sakya">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<div class="thumb tright">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Kalachakra_Mandala_Samye_Ling.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/00/Kalachakra_Mandala_Samye_Ling.jpg/220px-Kalachakra_Mandala_Samye_Ling.jpg" width="220" height="196" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/00/Kalachakra_Mandala_Samye_Ling.jpg/330px-Kalachakra_Mandala_Samye_Ling.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/00/Kalachakra_Mandala_Samye_Ling.jpg/440px-Kalachakra_Mandala_Samye_Ling.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1792" data-file-height="1593" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Kalachakra_Mandala_Samye_Ling.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>\nK\xc4\x81lacakra Tenfold Powerful symbol in <a href="/wiki/Stained_glass" title="Stained glass">stained glass</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p><a href="/wiki/Sakya_Trizin" title="Sakya Trizin">Sakya Trizin</a>, the present head of the Sakya lineage, has given the K\xc4\x81lacakra initiation many times and is a recognized master of the practice.</p>\n<p>The Sakya master H.E. <a href="/w/index.php?title=Chogye_Trichen_Rinpoche&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Chogye Trichen Rinpoche (page does not exist)">Chogye Trichen Rinpoche</a> is one of the main holders of the K\xc4\x81lacakra teachings. Chogye Rinpoche is the head of the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tsharpa&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Tsharpa (page does not exist)">Tsharpa</a> School, one of the three main schools of the Sakya tradition of Tibetan Buddhism.</p>\n<p>One of the previous Chogye Trichen Rinpoches, Khyenrab Choje (1436\xe2\x80\x9397), beheld the sustained vision of the female tantric deity <a href="/wiki/Vajrayogini" title="Vajrayogini">Vajrayogini</a> at Drak Yewa in central Tibet, and received extensive teachings and initiations directly from her. Two forms of Vajrayogini appeared out of the face of the rocks at Drak Yewa, one red in color and the other white, and they bestowed the K\xc4\x81lacakra initiation on Khyenrab Choje. When he asked if there was any proof of this, his attendant showed the master the kusha grass that Khyenrab Choje brought back with him from the initiation. It was unlike any kusha grass found in this world, with rainbow lights sparkling up and down the length of the dried blades of grass. This direct lineage from Vajrayogini is the \'shortest\', the most recent and direct, lineage of the K\xc4\x81lacakra empowerment and teachings that exists in this world. In addition to being known as the emanation of Manjushri, Khyenrab Choje had previously been born as many of the <a href="/wiki/Kings_of_Shambhala" title="Kings of Shambhala">Kings of Shambhala</a> as well as numerous Buddhist masters of India. These are some indications of his unique relationship to the K\xc4\x81lacakra tradition.</p>\n<p>Chogye Trichen Rinpoche is the holder of six different K\xc4\x81lacakra initiations, four of which, the Bulug, Jonang, Maitri-gyatsha, and Domjung, are contained within the Gyude Kuntu, the Collection of Tantras compiled by Jamyang Khyentse Wangpo and his disciple Loter Wangpo. Rinpoche has offered all six of these empowerments to Sakya Trizin, the head of the Sakya School of Tibetan Buddhism.</p>\n<p>Rinpoche has given the K\xc4\x81lacakra initiation in Tibet, Mustang, Kathmandu, Malaysia, the United States, Taiwan, and Spain, and is widely regarded as a definitive authority on K\xc4\x81lacakra. In 1988 he traveled to the United States, giving the initiation and complete instructions in the practice of the six-branch Vajrayoga of K\xc4\x81lacakra according to the Jonangpa tradition in Boston.</p>\n<p>Chogye Rinpoche has completed extensive retreat in the practice of K\xc4\x81lacakra, particularly of the six-branch yoga (sadangayoga) in the tradition of the Jonangpa school according to Jetsun <a href="/wiki/Taranatha" title="Taranatha">Taranatha</a>. In this way, Chogye Rinpoche has carried on the tradition of his predecessor Khyenrab Choje, the incarnation of the Shambhala kings who received the K\xc4\x81lacakra initiation from Vajrayogini herself. When Chogye Rinpoche was young, one of his teachers dreamed that Rinpoche was the son of the King of Shambhala, the pure land that upholds the tradition of K\xc4\x81lacakra. (See biography of Chogye Trichen Rinpoche in "Parting from the Four Attachments", Snow Lion Publications, 2003.)</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Jonang">Jonang</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Jonang">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Once deemed heretical by the 5th Dalai Lama and successors, and even thought to be extinct, the <a href="/wiki/Jonang" title="Jonang">Jonang</a> tradition has in fact survived and is now officially recognized by the Tibetan Government in exile as a fifth school of <a href="/wiki/Tibetan_Buddhism" title="Tibetan Buddhism">Tibetan Buddhism</a>. Jonang is particularly important in that it has preserved the K\xc4\x81lacakra practice lineage, especially of the completion stage practices. In fact, the K\xc4\x81lacakra is the main tantric practice in the Jonang tradition. <a href="/w/index.php?title=Khenpo_Kunga_Sherab_Rinpoche&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Khenpo Kunga Sherab Rinpoche (page does not exist)">Khenpo Kunga Sherab Rinpoche</a><sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">[13]</a></sup> is one contemporary Jonangpa master of K\xc4\x81lacakra.</p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Controversy">Controversy</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Controversy">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Prophesies_on_Holy_War">Prophesies on Holy War</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: Prophesies on Holy War">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>The K\xc4\x81lacakra Tantra has occasionally been a source of controversy in the west because the text contains passages which may be interpreted as demonizing <a href="/wiki/Islam" title="Islam">Islam</a>. This is principally because it contains the prophecy of a holy war between Buddhists and so-called "barbarians" (Skt. <i><a href="/wiki/Mleccha" title="Mleccha">mleccha</a></i>). One passage of the K\xc4\x81lacakra (\xc5\x9ari K\xc4\x81lacakra I. 161) reads, "The <a href="/wiki/Chakravartin" title="Chakravartin">Chakravartin</a> shall come out at the end of the age, from the city the gods fashioned on <a href="/wiki/Mount_Kailasa" class="mw-redirect" title="Mount Kailasa">Mount Kailasa</a>. He shall smite the barbarians in battle with his own four-division army, on the entire surface of the earth."</p>\n<p>This prophecy could also be understood to refer in part to the Islamic incursions into central Asia and India which destroyed the Buddhist religion in those regions. The prophecy includes detailed descriptions of the future invaders as well as suggested violent ways for the Buddhist teachings to survive these onslaughts.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">[14]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">[15]</a></sup></p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Symbolical_meaning">Symbolical meaning</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=20" title="Edit section: Symbolical meaning">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Though the K\xc4\x81lacakra prophesies a future religious war, this appears in conflict with the vows of <a href="/wiki/Mahayana" title="Mahayana">Mahayana</a> and <a href="/wiki/Theravada" title="Theravada">Theravada</a> Buddhist teachings that prohibit violence. According to <a href="/wiki/Alexander_Berzin_(scholar)" title="Alexander Berzin (scholar)">Alexander Berzin</a>, the K\xc4\x81lacakra is not advocating violence against people but rather against inner mental and emotional aggression that results in intolerance, hatred, violence and war. Fifteenth century Gelug commentor Kaydrubjey interprets "holy war" symbolically, teaching that it mainly refers to the inner battle of the religious practitioner against inner demonic and barbarian tendencies. This is the solution to violence, since according to the K\xc4\x81lacakra the outer conditions depend on the inner condition of the <a href="/wiki/Mindstream" class="mw-redirect" title="Mindstream">mindstreams</a> of beings. Viewed that way, the prophesied war takes place in the mind and emotions. It depicts the transformation of the archaic mentality of violence in the name of religion and ideology into sublime moral power, insight and spiritual wisdom.<sup id="cite_ref-studybuddhism.com_16-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-studybuddhism.com-16">[16]</a></sup></p>\n<p>One interpretation of Buddhist teachings that portray military conflict - such as elements of the K\xc4\x81lacakra Tantra and the <a href="/wiki/Epic_of_King_Gesar" title="Epic of King Gesar">Gesar Epic</a> - is that they may be taught for the sake of those who possess a karmic tendency towards militancy, for the purpose of taming their minds.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Words_to_watch#Unsupported_attributions" title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Words to watch"><span title="The material near this tag possibly uses too-vague attribution or weasel words. (April 2008)">who?</span></a></i>]</sup> The passages of the K\xc4\x81lacakra that address religious warfare can be viewed as teachings to turn away from any religious justification of war and violence, and to embrace the precepts of love and compassion.</p>\n<p>The controversial passages about the holy war, which most probably had been incorporated into the K\xc4\x81lacakra tradition during the time of massive advances of Islam into northern India when Buddhism had been on retreat, were later in modern time hijacked and used by several adventurous schemers both on the Left and on the Right to justify their political agendas. These questionable activities as well as the above-mentioned passages from old K\xc4\x81lacakra texts about the holy war and the ritual use of sexuality, prompted Victor and Victoria Trimondi, two German writers and philosophers, to launch a radical critique of the entire K\xc4\x81lacakra tradition.<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">[17]</a></sup> In contrast, Alexander Berzin, another prominent student of Tibetan Buddhism, seeks to provide a balanced and nuanced account of the same tradition.<sup id="cite_ref-studybuddhism.com_16-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-studybuddhism.com-16">[16]</a></sup></p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Iconography">Iconography</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=21" title="Edit section: Iconography">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Tantric iconography including sharp weapons, shields, and corpses similarly appears in conflict with those tenets of non-violence but instead represent the transmutation of aggression into a method for overcoming illusion and ego. Both K\xc4\x81lacakra and his <a href="/wiki/Dharmapala" title="Dharmapala">dharmapala</a> protector Vajravega hold a sword and shield in their paired second right and left hands. This is an expression of the Buddha\'s triumph over the attack of <a href="/wiki/Mara_(demon)" title="Mara (demon)">Mara</a> and his protection of all sentient beings.<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">[18]</a></sup> Symbolism researcher Robert Beer writes the following about tantric iconography of weapons and mentions the <a href="/wiki/Charnel_ground" title="Charnel ground">charnel ground</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Many of these weapons and implements have their origins in the wrathful arena of the battlefield and the funereal realm of the charnel grounds. As primal images of destruction, slaughter, sacrifice, and necromancy these weapons were wrested from the hands of the evil and turned - as symbols - against the ultimate root of evil, the self-cherishing conceptual identity that gives rise to the five poisons of ignorance, desire, hatred, pride, and jealousy. In the hands of siddhas, dakinis, wrathful and semi-wrathful yidam deities, protective deities or dharmapalas these implements became pure symbols, weapons of transformation, and an expression of the deities\' wrathful compassion which mercilessly destroys the manifold illusions of the inflated human ego.<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">[19]</a></sup></p>\n</blockquote>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="See_also">See also</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=22" title="Edit section: See also">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<table role="presentation" class="metadata mbox-small noprint selfref" style="background-color:#f9f9f9;border:1px solid #aaa;color:#000;width: 22em;">\n<tr>\n<td class="mbox-image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/18/Tibetan_wa_%2B_%28i%29.svg/40px-Tibetan_wa_%2B_%28i%29.svg.png" width="40" height="40" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/18/Tibetan_wa_%2B_%28i%29.svg/60px-Tibetan_wa_%2B_%28i%29.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/18/Tibetan_wa_%2B_%28i%29.svg/80px-Tibetan_wa_%2B_%28i%29.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="256" data-file-height="256" /></td>\n<td class="mbox-text plainlist" style="vertical-align:middle; font-size:95%;"><b>This article contains <a href="/wiki/Tibetan_script" class="mw-redirect" title="Tibetan script">Tibetan script</a>.</b> Without proper <a href="/wiki/Help:Multilingual_support_(Indic)#Tibetan" title="Help:Multilingual support (Indic)">rendering support</a>, you may see very small fonts, misplaced vowels or missing conjuncts instead of <a href="/wiki/Tibetan_script" class="mw-redirect" title="Tibetan script">Tibetan characters</a>.</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Chakravartin" title="Chakravartin">Chakravartin</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Horology" title="Horology">Horology</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Lodr%C3%B6_Ch%C3%B6kyong" title="Lodr\xc3\xb6 Ch\xc3\xb6kyong">Lodr\xc3\xb6 Ch\xc3\xb6kyong</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Kalachakra_stupa" title="Kalachakra stupa">Kalachakra stupa</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Kalki" title="Kalki">Kalki</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Kings_of_Shambhala" title="Kings of Shambhala">Kings of Shambhala</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Shambhala_Buddhism" title="Shambhala Buddhism">Shambhala Buddhism</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Shambhala" title="Shambhala">Shambhala</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="References">References</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kalachakra&amp;action=edit&amp;section=23" title="Edit section: References">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class="reflist columns references-column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;">\n<ol class="references">\n<li id="cite_note-Rite-1"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Rite_1-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Gyatso, Tenzin (1985). Hopkins, Jeffrey, ed. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?ei=eb7LUKWdBNPHqAHN7YGIAw&amp;id=BdgKAAAAYAAJ&amp;dq=0861710282&amp;q=planets#search_anchor"><i>Kalachakra Tantra: Rite of Initiation for the Stage of Generation, a Commentary on the text of Kay-drup-ge-lek-bel-sang-bo by Tenzin Gyatso, the Fourteenth Dalai Lama, and the Text Itself</i></a> <span style="font-size:85%;">(Octavo, soft.)</span> (2nd. ed.). London: Wisdom Publications. p.&#160;212. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0861710282" title="Special:BookSources/0861710282">0861710282</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">15 December</span> 2012</span>. <q>The external K\xc4\x81lacakra refers to all of the environment - the mountains, fences, homes, planets, constellations of stars, solar systems, and so forth.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AKalachakra&amp;rft.aufirst=Tenzin&amp;rft.aulast=Gyatso&amp;rft.btitle=Kalachakra+Tantra%3A+Rite+of+Initiation+for+the+Stage+of+Generation%2C+a+Commentary+on+the+text+of+Kay-drup-ge-lek-bel-sang-bo+by+Tenzin+Gyatso%2C+the+Fourteenth+Dalai+Lama%2C+and+the+Text+Itself&amp;rft.date=1985&amp;rft.edition=2nd.&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.isbn=0861710282&amp;rft.pages=212&amp;rft.place=London&amp;rft.pub=Wisdom+Publications&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fei%3Deb7LUKWdBNPHqAHN7YGIAw%26id%3DBdgKAAAAYAAJ%26dq%3D0861710282%26q%3Dplanets%23search_anchor&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-2"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20140327125134/http://kalachakranet.org/kalachakra_tantra_history.html">Kalachakra History</a> //archived 16 Sep 2014</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-3"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.thewildrose.net/tibetan_buddhism.html">"Tibetan Buddhism - Kalachakra Tantra"</a>. Thewildrose.net<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">2014-06-02</span></span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AKalachakra&amp;rft.btitle=Tibetan+Buddhism+-+Kalachakra+Tantra&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.pub=Thewildrose.net&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.thewildrose.net%2Ftibetan_buddhism.html&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-4"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Kilty, G <i>Ornament of Stainless Light</i>, Wisdom 2004, <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-86171-452-0" title="Special:BookSources/0-86171-452-0">0-86171-452-0</a></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-5"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-5">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Tibetan Astrology by Philippe Cornu, Shambala 1997, <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/1-57062-217-5" title="Special:BookSources/1-57062-217-5">1-57062-217-5</a></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-6"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Das, Sarat Chandra (1882). <i>Contributions on the Religion and History of Tibet</i>. First published in: <i>Journal of the Asiatic Society of Bengal</i>, Vol. LI. Reprint: Manjushri Publishing House, Delhi. 1970, pp. 81-82.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-7"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-7">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.thewildrose.net/tibetan_buddhism.html">Tibetan Buddhism</a> from Website of the Wild Rose Dreamers Lodge</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-8"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.dalailama.com/teachings/kalachakra-initiations">Kalachakra Initiations by His Holiness the Dalai Lama</a></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-hplahaulspiti-9"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-hplahaulspiti_9-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20140819101915/http://hplahaulspiti.nic.in/spititouristplaces.htm">"Official Website of Lahaul-Spiti District Administration"</a>. Deputy Commissioner, Lahaul and Spiti. Archived from <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://hplahaulspiti.nic.in/SpitiTouristPlaces.htm#KYE">the o